1 Introduction

The 2007-2008 Financial Crisis devastated the world economy beginning with the meltdown in the American sub-prime mortgage market, which due to the excessive borrowing and lending in the previous years provoked panic and sparked a global credit crisis, that further amplified the fall of assets in all sorts of industries in the internationally interlinked markets with the eventual worldwide recession (Arner, 2009). During and after the unfolding crisis, millions of people lost their jobs, especially the younger population (Choudhry et al., 2012), with the long-term effect on the global unemployment level estimated in 2013 to be 60 million higher than the pre-crisis trends predicted (ILO, 2014). Furthermore, a large number of people saw their houses and life savings dwindle in value due to the bursts of the housing and other industries bubbles, with their hedge funds and investment accounts suffering heavy losses due to circumstantial imposed widespread fire sales of assets (Bernanke, 2018). The outcome of the economic fallout led to a surge in the general level of poverty, with the most severely affected countries having to cut significant portions of their budgets on education, healthcare, and social security at a time of utmost necessity for the numerous individuals in distress (Karanikolos et al., 2013). In extreme cases, countries such as Greece and Cyprus saw their economies contract in the next 6 years by around 30 and 10 percent of their GDP (Hermann, 2017), while the OECD countries, which had also suffered a banking crisis as a consequence, had in 2014 a GDP growth trend lower by 5.5 percent than the pre-crisis growth trends predicted (Ollivaud & Turner, 2014). The dire economic conditions in which the young people could not get integrated into the workforce as swiftly as the previous generations had profound social effects, as they failed to take advantage of some of their most productive years and establish the financial fundamentals for their own households (Choudhry et al., 2012), living through the so-called by some economists âLost decadeâ (Hermann, 2017). Moreover, all of these factors also partially contributed to the increase in global suicide levels and the spread of mental illnesses in the societies of various nations (Karanikolos et al., 2016)

Naturally, in order to be able to prevent such terrible recessions, governments, economists, and market players have to study thoroughly the flaws of the economic framework and come up with improvements and instruments to safeguard the economies in the future. Institutions, statisticians, and financial analysts have been gathering for decades ever-increasing amounts of data on all sorts of economic subjects and phenomena, which must be processed and interpreted with the most up-to-date data analysis and machine learning techniques to provide elaborate instruments for efficient economic analysis and actions. The focus of this research will investigate one of the paramount factors that exacerbated and subsequently also caused the 2007-2008 Financial Crisis, which was the failure of the market participantsâ evaluation methods to offer accurate and rigorous estimates of the real value of companies, causing chaos and uncertainty among the ranks of the financial market participants that could no longer trust and deal transactions with their partners, even if the affected firms had otherwise sound balance sheets (Bernanke, 2018). Thus, at the height of the crisis, the freezing of the liquidity of the whole credit market commenced, leaving numerous potential business projects and companies in need of liquid assets without any investment source, which consequently led to significant capital losses in the economy and the bankruptcy of numerous firms with the notable case of Lehman Brothers investment bank filing for the highest bankruptcy in history with 680 billion dollars in assets and 100,000 creditors (Arner, 2009).

Therefore, in order to provide an accessible framework for the analysis of stock prices, this paper states the following research question: âTo what degree do various financial variables aid in the prediction of stock prices?â

For this research, a data set is going to be used, containing raw data of the most important financial metrics of the companies listed in the S&P 500 index in the 2020 fiscal year. The S&P 500 firms represent a suitable object of study, as it consists of the biggest companies in diverse industries in the United States, which also has the biggest economy in the world and makes it automatically an example to be followed by all the other countries. A 6-Step extensive data analysis strategy will be employed with the appropriate data science methods in order to better understand the data set and investigate the research question. After the Research Understanding introductory phase, Datat preparation of the given dataset will be conducted, and then the investigation of the variables of significance in the Exploratory Data Analysis phase will take place. Thereafter, the appropriate models and algorithms will be utilized to test the research hypotheses and interpret their usefulness in the Modeling and Evaluation stages, with the corresponding final conclusion.

2 Theoretical Framework

2.1 The ability of stock price prediction

A stock index is a collection of equities or securities, which is normally computed from the market capital of constituents. As such, the S&P 500 stock index provides a summary of the overall market performance of the US and helps its investors in their investing activities. It is the most widely used benchmark for measuring the performance of US-based stocks, as it constitutes around 83 % of the market capitalization of all regularly traded stocks on the New York, American, and NASDAQ exchanges, and covers almost all of the 500 largest companies ranked by market value (Siegel & Schwartz, 2006). Consequently, the prediction of such a stock index is of high importance.

Research proves that the ability of companies to predict stock prices is a crucial and complex endeavor for stock companies, policy-makers, and investors alike (Bekiros et al., 2016). This is because accurate stock price predictions enable the ability to make informed investment decisions, informed risk management, and enhanced financial performance (Wang, 2014). The leading example, which demonstrates the need for data-driven investment strategies is the illusion of the long-lasting Efficient Market Hypothesis, through which it is proposed that the pricing of the markets is efficient and all the available information is reflected in the prices (Fama, 1970). Meanwhile, financial crises such as the one in 2008, prove that investors are not always rational, and even by obtaining perfect information, investment strategies might not be optimal due to emotional barriers (Ying et al., 2019). As such, taking into account both the favor and criticism of the Efficient Market Hypothesis, it can be claimed that the information can either be reflected in the prices or not (Malkiel, 2003). Since there is no proven consensus on price prediction strategies given the recent turmoil in the financial theory, conventional models that use financial information are expected to correctly predict the stock prices at 50% of the time or more which is no significantly different prediction value of simple random chance. The research models will merely use the financial information to test whether the financial information will present statistical significance in predicting stock prices by being in favor of the Efficient Market Hypothesis.

Following this realization, the main hypothesis of this research can be constructed:

H1: The proportion of companies that are correctly predicted for their future stock prices is more than 50%.

2.2 Financial Determinants of Price

Considering the previous disastrous impacts of the financial crises in the near history, it became evident that institutions and companies created their own ways in predicting stock prices. Even though the strategies use various statistical and financial techniques, there is a financial theory presented that stock prices are influenced by a wide range of financial information, which collectively reflects the health and performance of a company. This information usually comes in the form of financial ratios and inputs in the financial statements of the company. By presenting the summary of the reasons and the current situation in predicting stock prices, the theoretical background of the 4 main determinants of stock prices will be observed and necessary hypotheses will be stated.

2.2.1 Dividend and Dividend Yield

The neoclassical school of economic thought theorized that companies essentially aim to maximize profits (Mulligan, 1986). The general motivation of the theory is to redistribute a portion of profits to the companyâs shareholders in the form of dividends. In this sense, paying dividends serves a common purpose which is to attract more investors to the company by offering them a stable return in the long run (Feldstein and Green, 1983). Consequently, just like companies, individuals are also motivated by maximizing profits where investors are more likely to buy stocks with higher dividend yield where on the contrary investments might not be considered with no dividend income (Friends and Puckett, 1964). Furthermore, there is substantial econometric evidence that hoarding cash can be value reducing for companies in the long run due to inefficient allocation of capital (Denis and Sibilkov, 2010). Overall, dividend payouts are a way to signal the financial performance of the company as well as maintaining constant enhancement for investments. The aforementioned reasons about dividend payments and yields can boost up the demand for stocks which in turn pushes up the stock price. Therefore, the following hypotheses are constructed:

H2a: Companies that pay dividends have a higher price prediction compared to the companies that do not pay dividends.

H2b: Companies that have a higher dividend yield have a higher price prediction compared to the companies that do not pay dividends.

2.2.2 Earnings Per Share and Sectors

Another financial metric that is presented in the quarterly financial statements of the companies which is an indication of the companyâs profitability for every share the company is divided to. The EPS itself is forecasted by analysts to create expectations in the market where higher than expected EPS growth brings positive investor sentiment which increases the stock prices (Lander et al., 1997). The increase in demand is explained in another research where the study showed that investors tend to show a bias towards future growth in EPS by judging past expectations (de Wet, 2013). However, there is also contrasting research where evidence suggests that EPS and stock prices do not always go in the same direction mainly due to macroeconomic risks and company related effects (Islam et al., 2014). As stock prices reflect a future potential on earnings, the ratio may show differentiations based on the sector that the company is operating in since some sectors are profitable in certain conditions. For instance, the earnings for the healthcare sector excessed other sectors during the COVID pandemic due to developments of vaccines and treatments (Esparcia and LÃ³pez, 2022). On the other hand, as the outside conditions are subject to change and every sector presents its own advantages, sector profitability presents cyclicality which may not be consistent. However, due to the added value of some specific sectors, such as the difference between the products of technology and consumer discretionary sectors, the effects of sectors are thought of to be relevant. Considering the overview, it can be seen that even though EPS is not sufficient by itself to determine financial health, it still is a valid metric to signal profit expectations of a company. Thus, the following hypothesis is stated:

H2c: Companies that have a higher earnings per share ratio have a higher price prediction compared to companies that have a lower earnings per share

H2d: The sector of the companies have no effect on the stock price.

2.2.3 Price Sales and Price Book Ratio

Price Sales and Price Book ratios are essential valuations metrics that combine the relationship between the market value of a stock and the inherent value of the companyâs financials. Price sales ratio indicates how much investors are willing to pay for each dollar of sales (Vruwink et al., 2007) and it is calculated through dividing the market cap by total revenue. A way to interpret the P/S ratio is to understand its fluctuations where a higher ratio means that buyers are willing to pay more for the stock compared to the companies that generate the same revenue. However, there is also consensus in the theory that high P/S companies are classified as overvalued and may have downward price pressure for their stock in the long run (Danielson and Lipton, 2015).

On the other hand, the price book ratio presents a companyâs market cap to its book value where it signals the value per share that the investors will receive in case of liquidation of the company. The ratio is utilized to assess the valuation of market price to compare with its intrinsic value where previous research argued that if the ratio is deep above or below 1 it is a signal for overvaluation or undervaluation respectively (Bernard, 1994). Therefore, the econometric evidence showed that the price-book ratio explains the price variances at 66% of the time along with ROE (Bernard, 1994). Furthermore, there is also valid criticism as book value does not take into account intangible assets, it is not a reliable indicator for non-capital intensive companies (Berk and DeMarzo, 2019). Thus, for certain companies price book ratio is not as significant in determining the stock price as price sales ratio. The findings in the previous literature and theory suggest that higher price sales ratio tend to boost up valuations and expectations whereas higher price book ratio signals overvaluation and breaks up demand for the stock. Taking into account the background knowledge, following hypotheses will be tested.

H2e: Companies with higher price-sales ratio have a higher price prediction compared to companies with low price-sales ratio.

H2f: Companies with lower price-book ratio have a higher price prediction compared to companies with high price-sales ratio.

3 Data Preprocessing

The raw data is gathered using Kaggle that is an online community for data science contents where various datasets on a wide range of topics are present. The metadata presents that the dataset is constructed by a Kaggle collaborator by utilizing the online data collection center DataHub.io (https://datahub.io/) which is gathered using the data from July 2020. In this sense, besides the financial information, the raw data also includes the SEC filings for all companies in order for the financial information to be verified that shows the validity of the dataset even though the column with the links are deleted for the sake of the econometric analysis. Besides that, a dummy variable called Dividend is created manually if the Dividend.Yield is different than 0. A dummy variable of PositiveEBITDA is also created that gets a value of 1 if the company has positive earnings which may have an affect on the price that lays the foundations of the data collection methodology. Finally, the reason for the selection of S&P 500 index rather than the others is because it contains the largest 505 public companies in the US which indicates an overall economic health. The following link directs to the dataset which ensures the replicability of the research: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/paytonfisher/sp-500-companies-with-financial-information/data


Before conducting a statistical analysis and create a predictive model, the components of the dataset are investigated thoroughly. The csv file is imported to R.

In order to conduct a statistical research, we need to prepare the data set for a proper analysis where the outliers are adjusted and the missing values are handled. In this sense, the data preprocessing stage is essential to obtain a viable trend for the regression analysis and a prediction.

Considering this, the missing values are denoted as NAâs in the summary where the data set contains 8 missing values for the variable Price.Book and 2 missing values for the variable Price.Earnings.

It is a known fact that the largest companies in the S&P500 index are selected based on their market cap. However, since the market cap is subject to change on a daily basis, it is not a good indicator to capture financial health. Therefore, to indicate outliers in the dataframe, earnings per share as a ratio is used, that not only has a direct affect on market cap but also shows an indication for financial performance which changes less frequently. Thus, in order to capture the outlier companies in the index, we will be observing the Earnings.Share variable.

ggplot( data = financial_data ) +
    geom_histogram( aes( x = Earnings.Share ), binwidth = 0.5 )


Based on the above output, we observe a bell curve shaped distribution for the Earnings.Share amongst the companies. As the data visualizations are not always clear in showing the trend, a boxplot is created to calculate the outliers.

ggplot( data = financial_data, aes( y = Earnings.Share ) ) +
     geom_boxplot()

summary(financial_data$Earnings.Share)
     Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  -28.010   1.490   2.890   3.754   5.140  44.090

All data that is either above the third quartile or below the first quartile by 1.5 times the interquartile range (IQR) is tagged as an outlier treated as is. In this sense, the IQR is the difference between the third and the first quartiles which is 3.65 (5.140 - 1.490). In this sense the upper boundary for outliers is 10.615 and the lower boundary is -3.985. Therefore, the companies that have an earnings per share that is above 10.615 or below -3.985 are considered as outliers. In order to treat outliers, they will be imputed by missing values and will be treated as one.

financial_data_noutliers = mutate( financial_data, Earnings.Share = ifelse(Earnings.Share < -3.985 | Earnings.Share > 10.615, NA, Earnings.Share)) 
summary(financial_data_noutliers$Earnings.Share)
     Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
   -3.720   1.498   2.810   3.178   4.750  10.400      41

To check all the missing values in the dataset, the function gg_missing_var() is used that is taken from the naniar library.

gg_miss_var( financial_data_noutliers, show_pct = TRUE )

It can be seen that missing values are contained in the variables Price.Earnings and Price.Book both of them having less than 2% of missing values. Finally around 8% of the data in the variable Earning.Share are missing due to outliers. An essential way to treat missing values is to replace them with random values where the built-in library called hmisc is used to call the impute() function:

financial_data_noutliers $ Price.Earnings      = impute( financial_data_noutliers $ Price.Earnings     , 'random' )
financial_data_noutliers $ Price.Book          = impute( financial_data_noutliers $ Price.Book, 'random' ) 
financial_data_noutliers $ Earnings.Share      = impute( financial_data_noutliers $ Earnings.Share    , 'random' ) 
gg_miss_var( financial_data_noutliers, show_pct = TRUE )

cleaned_financial_data <- financial_data_noutliers
write.csv(cleaned_financial_data, "cleaned_financial_data.csv")

4 Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

In order to increase our understanding of the price per share of a company and the variables that affect this price, we will make use of a further exploratory data analysis to examine the relevant relationships in more detail. But, to better understand the variables that affect our target variable, let us first further examine all facets of the price of a share.

4.1 Investigating the target variable Price

First, we generate a simple overview of the range of the Price. When examining this, one can deduce that the price of a share in the S&P 500 varies greatly from a minimum of 2.82 US-dollars up to 1806.06 US-Dollars, with a mean price of 103.83$.

summary (cleaned_financial_data$Price)
     Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
     2.82   46.25   73.92  103.83  116.54 1806.06

To further examine the distribution of the price of a share in the data, a density plot is created.

ggplot (data = cleaned_financial_data)+
  geom_density (aes(x = Price), color ="black", fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5)+
  ggtitle ("General distribution of the price of a share of a company in the S&P 500")+
  xlab ("Price of a share of a company in the S&P 500") + ylab ("Density")

We see in the plot above, that the price of the shares is distributed very one-sidedly, with most of the prices of the shares falling between 0 and around 300 US-dollars. As such, the distribution of the Price is highly skewed to the right, with only a very little proportion of the stocks of the S&P 500 costing more than 300$.

4.2 Investigation of Binary Variables:

4.2.1 Determinant 1: Positive EBITDA

From the bar plot below we can see that most companies in the S&P 500 index list have positive Earnings, which is approximately 86.73% of the total.

ggplot (data = cleaned_financial_data)+
  geom_bar (aes(x=PositiveEBITDA))+
  xlab("Company having positive EBITDA")

mean(cleaned_financial_data$PositiveEBITDA.Binary)
  [1] 0.8673267

In order to better observe the relationship of the presence of earnings of a company and the stock price we construct a box plot and density graphs for the corresponding variables.

ggplot (data = cleaned_financial_data)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = PositiveEBITDA, y = Price), fill = c("red", "blue"))+
  xlab("Company having positive EBITDA")+ ylab("Price of a share")

ggplot (data = cleaned_financial_data)+
  geom_density(aes(x = Price, fill = PositiveEBITDA), alpha = 0.5)+
  xlab("Price of a share")+ ylab("Density")

The results do not show a significant difference in price for the firms with positive or non positive earnings. Most of the firms of both kinds are found in the 0 to 250 stock price range, while the firms with stock price higher than 300 show the trend of having positive earnings, even though they represent a small part of the data set.

ggplot(cleaned_financial_data, aes(x = Sector, fill = PositiveEBITDA)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion")+
  scale_fill_manual( values = c( "red", "blue" ) ) +
  theme( axis.text.x = element_text( angle = -45 ) )

A bar-plot of the Sector values filled by the positive EBITDA values shows a similar proportion of the EBITDA across different sectors, with the exceptions of the Financial Industry, where most firms actually report non-negative earnings. Therefore, if we would want to develop a model of stock price predictions specifically for the financial sector, we would need to take into account its specific approach in regards to the EBITDA variable.

A T-test is going to be run in order to investigate whether firms with positive EBITDA have an effect on the stock price target variable.

t.test(Price ~ PositiveEBITDA, data = cleaned_financial_data)
  
    Welch Two Sample t-test
  
  data:  Price by PositiveEBITDA
  t = -2.4945, df = 209.34, p-value = 0.01339
  alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group No and group Yes is not equal to 0
  95 percent confidence interval:
   -44.323421  -5.192338
  sample estimates:
   mean in group No mean in group Yes 
           82.35746         107.11534

From the t-test between the Price and the presence of Earnings of a company, with a p-value of 0.01339 lower than the significance level of 0.05 percent, we can conclude that the PositiveEBITDA has indeed a significant effect on the Price of stock.

4.2.2 Determinant 2: The paying of a dividend

First, let us examine the distribution of the variable âDividendâ.

ggplot (data = cleaned_financial_data)+
  geom_bar (aes(x=Dividend))

From the barplot, we can deduce that a big majority of the companies in the S&P 500 do pay dividends. To further examine whether a company that pays dividends affects the price of a share of that company, we are making use of a box plot and a density plot.

ggplot (data = cleaned_financial_data)+
  geom_density(aes(x = Price, fill = Dividend), alpha = 0.5)+
  xlab("Price of a share")+ ylab("Density")

The density plot demonstrates that while the majority of the companies in both groups fall within the price range of 0 US dollars to 500 US dollars, the companies that do not pay dividends are quite consistently more often found in the price range of over 200 dollars. This conclusion is somewhat supported by the box plot, as it demonstrates that the majority of the values of the companies that do not pay dividends are more spread out into the higher price regions than the companies that pay dividends, although the median of both groups is quite similar. But since these results suggest contradicting evidence to H2a, we further examine the relationship between the variables Dividend and Price with the help of a two-sample t-test.

t.test(Price ~ Dividend, data = cleaned_financial_data)

The statistically significant results (at the .05 level) of the two sample t-test suggest that there is a statistically significant difference in the average prices in the two groups. This will be more thoroughly explored later during modeling.

4.3 Investigation of Numerical Variables:

Moving on to the numerical variables, a correlation plot and correlation panels are constructed to observe the effects of the variables with each other.

variable_list = c( "Price","Price.Earnings","Dividend.Yield","Earnings.Share","X52.Week.Low","X52.Week.High","EBITDA","Price.Sales", "Price.Book")

pairs.panels( cleaned_financial_data[ , variable_list ] )

ggcorrplot(cor_matrix, type = "lower", lab = TRUE)

From the correlation table, it can be observed that most of the variables have low levels of correlation with each other, most of the numbers representing a lower than 0.25 deviation from 0. However, The X52.Week.Low and X52.Week.High variables have an almost perfect correlation of 0.98 which is not a surprising result, considering that in this data set they are used to represent a measure of the variance of the stock price. Furthermore in order not to overestimate the effect of the variance in the regression model, one of the variables shall be dropped, which will be the X52.Week.High due to the fact that even though it has a higher correlation with the target variable, the X52.Week.Low has smaller correlations with all the other explanatory variables in the data set.

Additionally, considering that the Binary variables in the data set describe a similar phenomena as the Dividend.Yield and EBITDA variables, we should do a corresponding Pearson correlation test for the binary variables.

From the results, the conclusion can be made that with a correlation of 0.5593271 for the Dividend and Dividend.Yield variables, if we donât want to overestimate their effect on the target variables in some models, we should drop one of the variables. 4.4 Additional variables of interest

4.4.1 Sector

To examine whether the sector in which a S&P 500 company operates influences the price of a share of the company, a box plot is created.

sector_colors <- c("white", "yellow", "blue", "green", "red", "orange", "purple", "brown", "pink", "lightblue", "grey")


ggplot(data = cleaned_financial_data) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = Sector, y = Price, fill = Sector)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 25)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = sector_colors) +  
  ylim(0, 500)

As evident in the box plot, the stock prices of the companies can drastically differ between the financial sectors. Consequently, this box plot provides contradictory evidence to the H2d. To further examine, whether the financial sector in which a company operates has an effect on the stock price an ANOVA is used.

anova_sec_price = aov(Price ~ Sector, data = cleaned_financial_data)
print (summary(anova_sec_price))
               Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
  Sector       10  303235   30324   1.701 0.0775 .
  Residuals   494 8804442   17823                 
  ---
  Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The results of the Analysis of Variance show that there are no statistically significant differences (at the .05 level) between the different financial sectors of the S&P 500 companies and the stock prices of the companies. As such, we can conclude that we have found support for the Hypothesis, that the sector of the companies have no effect on the stock price.

5 Data preparation

In this stage, the dataset will be prepared for the modeling section. Here, the cleaned_financial_data dataset is partitioned randomly into two groups: train set (80%) and test set (20%). Here, the partition() function is used from the liver package, by inputting a random seed beforehand:

set.seed( 6 )

data_sets = partition( data = cleaned_financial_data, prob = c( 0.8, 0.2 ) )

train_set = data_sets $ part1
test_set  = data_sets $ part2

actual_test  = test_set $ Price

Since the target variable of the model is numeric, based on the random partition, we will validate the partition by testing whether the variance of the variable Price differs in both groups of train and test. In order to do this, an F-test is conducted with a significance level of 5%. Based on this, following hypotheses are stated:

\[ \bigg\{ \begin{matrix} H_0: \sigma^2_1 = \sigma^2_2\\ H_a: \sigma^2_1 \neq \sigma^2_2 \end{matrix} \]


In this sense, the null hypothesis states that the variance of the variable Price does not differ for train and test groups. On the other hand, the alternative hypothesis claims that for both groups, the variance differs.

var.test(train_set $ Price, test_set $ Price, alternative = "two.sided")

It can be observed from the above output that the test outcome has an F value of 1.0323 and a p-value of 0.8598. It can be seen that since the p-value is larger than the significance level of 5% (0.8598 > 0.05), we do not reject the null hypothesis. This means that we do not have sufficient evidence to claim that the variance for the âPriceâ differs between train and test group. To validate the partition in terms of population mean a Two Sample t-test is conducted to observe whether the sample means for two group differ. In this sense, the following hypotheses are created:

\[ \bigg\{ \begin{matrix} H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2\\ H_a: \mu_1 \neq \mu_2 \end{matrix} \]


In this sense, the null hypothesis states that the mean of the variable Price does not differ for train and test groups. On the other hand, the alternative hypothesis claims that for both groups, the mean differs.

t.test(train_set $ Price, test_set $ Price, var.equal=TRUE)

It can be seen that since the p-value is larger than the significance level of 5% (0.5749 > 0.05), we do not reject the null hypothesis. This means that we do not have sufficient evidence to claim that the mean for the âPriceâ differs between train and test group. The above interpretations for the statistical tests indicate that the partition for the target variable Price is valid.

6 Modeling

Considering the theoretical framework and outputs of the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), out of the 13 predictors in the dataset, the following variables are the ones that are detected to have an influence on the target variable and deemed to be important: Price.Earnings, Dividend.Yield, Earnings.Share, EBITDA, PositiveEBITDA, Price.Sales, Price.Book and Dividend. Given the variables and data partitioning, different algorithms will be utilized to determine the effects of financial information on price.

The model will be created by calling the built-in lm() function in R and use summary() function to analyze the significance and the coefficients of the variables.

6.3 Regression Model Verification


After the model is created, it is important to check whether it satisfies the assumptions and requirements of the modeling section. In this sense, the plot() function will be used

plot(reg_final)


The first graph that shows the trend between residuals and the fitted value present a linear trend in which any curves and parabolic relations are eluded. Thus, the first assumption of linearity is satisfied. For the second graph, Q-Q residuals are presented where a trend for the relationship between the theoretical quantiles and standardized residuals are fitted. This allows the research to observe the assumption of normality of residuals. In this sense, even though there is slight curvature in the beginning and at the end of the trend, the graph shows a positive linear and the majority of the observations lie on the trend which proves the normality assumption. Furthermore, it is observed from the above output that as the vertical spread of the points in the plot is not systematically nonuniform, the constant variance assumption is not violated. Finally, the independence assumption hold for the research sample since the stock price of companies tend not to affect each other.

7.4 Hypothesis Evaluation and Discussion

Considering the regression model, it can be concluded that companies with higher earnings per share, higher EBITDA and higher price to sales ratio are expected to have a higher stock price. In contrast, paying dividends and the dividend yield itself lower the price prediction for the stocks.

The most significant financial determinant of the stock prices is the dividend yield, earnings per share, EBITDA, price-sales ratio and whether the company is paying dividends, In this regard, for every one unit increase in price-earnings ratio the stock price goes up by $0.5001, for every one unit increase in dividend yield the stock price goes down by $14.25, for every one unit increase in the earnings per share the stock price goes up by $11.16, for every one unit increase in EBITDA the stock price goes up by $2.695 * 10\(^-9\), for every one unit increase in the price-sales ratio the stock price goes up by $5.321, and finally if the company is paying dividends, the stock price goes down by $29.43.

Taking into account that the model explains 16.28% of the variance for the prices, it correctly predicts the stock prices only 16.28% of the times that is not in line with the initial hypothesis of the research. Therefore we do not have statistically significant evidence to state that stock prices can be predicted accurately at 50% of the times simply using the financial information of companies and therefore we do not accept H1 (proportion of correctly predicted stocks is at least 50%). Based on this, sub-hypotheses give insights about the model and further research. In this sense, H2c is accepted (companies that have a higher earnings per share ratio have a higher price prediction), H2d is accepted (the sector of the companies have no effect on the stock price) as presented in the EDA, H2e is accepted (companies with higher price-sales ratio have a higher price prediction). On the other hand, H2a is not accepted (companies that pay dividends have a higher price prediction), H2b is not accepted (companies that have a higher dividend yield have a higher price prediction), H2f is not accepted (companies with lower price-book ratio have a higher price prediction) as price-book ratio is insignificant for price prediction at \(\alpha=0.05\).

8 Conclusion

With the challenges of the financial information on the determinants of stock prices, the impacts of financial information on the movements of the stock price were challenged where the prolonged criticism on the Efficient Market Hypothesis stated that not all available information is reflected on the prices. In light of the previous literature on the issue, as it is believed that data modeling can conclude a solution, the research investigated the financial determinants of stock prices by taking into account the research question of âTo what extent does the financial information of companies have an effects on stock prices?â. The analysis initially observed how all variables in the dataset interacted with the target variable Price. Following, based on the statistical significance of variables and the previous literature, the research classifies the financial information that are important for determining the stock price on several variables namely, Price.Earnings, Dividend.Yield,Earnings.Share, EBITDA, PositiveEBITDA, Price.Sales, Price.Book, Dividend. By utilizing the given variables, the research undertakes three modeling stages: multiple regression model, CART algorithm and the random forest algorithm.

Considering the objective and the methodology of the research, the results of the data analysis suggest that financial information of companies are not statistically sufficient in determining the stock prices by providing evidence from the companies in the S&P 500 index. In this sense, H1 of the research is not accepted. Even though the null hypothesis does not have sufficient support, there is robust evidence that certain financial information contribute in determining the stock price. In this sense, the sub-hypotheses H2c, H2d and H2e are accepted. In other words, the research concludes that financial information is not enough by itself in predicting stock prices although information on the price-earnings ratio, dividend yield, earnings per share, EBITDA, price-sales ratio and paying dividend has a significant affect as a determinant for stock price. Therefore, as mentioned in the theoretical background, the research contributes to the existing literature by providing data-driven evidence that the Efficient Market Hypothesis no longer holds and financial information is not enough in determining stock prices.

All in all, the research contributes to the literature by laying the importance of data science in the financial sector where conventional theory may fail due to the paradigm shifts in the area through financial crises. The aforementioned findings of the research can be attributed to two main reasons that can be labeled as the limitations of the research. Firstly, with the developments in globalization and interconnectedness of economies in the recent century, created an environment where financial markets are more vulnerable to global macroeconomic condition as well as foreign economic policies. The rapid access to information undermines the importance of financial information as changes in prices can be explained by various elements such as regional politics and economic development. Additionally, with the improvements in globalization, changes in a stock market may impact the others which makes the system inter-dependent. Therefore, market valuation of a company may also reflect the developments in other markets as investors also take into account the financial information of competitors or subcontractor which makes financial information less significant as a determinant of the stock price. Secondly, with the effects of globalization, the time that the financial information is reflected on the prices is also a matter of discussion with the developments of technology. As the amount of news about a company grows with the access to technology, it also gets faster for the market to internalize the information and reflect the news on the prices. In other words, the absorption of financial information is faster which also makes its importance fade rapidly. Therefore, the small time frame that the financial information is reflected on the prices may make financial information less important as other determinants also take part in the meantime.

The given reasons present recommendations for investors and financial professionals as shown in the introduction section to prevent future financial crises and give logical investment decisions. It is important to take into account that investors should not merely look into the balance sheet of companies and decide on an investment strategy. Data driven investment strategies should also take into account macroeconomic variables and market sentiment when creating a predictive machine learning model. Furthermore, the research gives insights for policy makers where regulation on capital markets should also aim at the transparency of non-financial information to prevent future financial crises which is shown to play a key role for the savings and the prosperity of the society. In this sense, institutions should take strict measures for disinformation and manipulation that utilize non-financial information to distort the market predictions.

Finally, the research lays the foundation for future research recommendations where the limitations and the assumptions are adjusted. Further research can take into account various macroeconomic variables to observe how much financial information play a role in predicting stock prices relative to the macroeconomic condition. Another aspect to be challenged can be to observe a cross-sectional time series analysis where the importance of financial information on determining stock prices can be analyzed before and after a financial crisis.
